    "caption": "Every single one of those thirty thousand quills is a warning.",
    "shortDescription": "Porcupines are covered in up to thirty thousand quills that sit loosely in their skin — when a predator gets too close, the quills detach on contact and are nearly impossible to pull out because they have tiny backward-facing barbs. Porcupines can't throw them, but they don't have to. Fun fact: A porcupine rattles its quills together to make a loud warning buzz before any quills are needed."
